[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 8.7: Adverse Event Detection in Clinical Text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium-Complex · **Phase:** Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.03-0.10 per note
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A patient receives a new blood pressure medication. Two weeks later, they mention to their cardiologist that they've been dizzy every morning since starting it. The cardiologist documents "patient reports orthostatic dizziness, likely related to new amlodipine" in the progress note. That note lives in the EHR. Nobody extracts it. Nobody routes it to pharmacovigilance. Nobody connects it to the three other patients in the same health system who reported the same symptom on the same medication at the same dose.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Six months later, a patient safety officer pulls charts for a quality review and finds 47 mentions of the same adverse reaction buried across progress notes, nursing assessments, and discharge summaries. The signal was there the entire time. It was documented. It just wasn't surfaced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the baseline state of adverse event (AE) detection in healthcare: voluntary reporting systems that capture maybe 5-10% of actual adverse events. The FDA's MedWatch system depends on clinicians taking the time to fill out a form. Hospital incident reporting systems depend on someone recognizing the event as reportable. Spontaneous reporting has been the backbone of post-market drug safety surveillance for decades, and it consistently misses the majority of events. Studies suggest that voluntary reporting captures between 1% and 13% of actual adverse drug events, depending on the severity and the institution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The information we need is already being documented in clinical text. Every progress note, every nursing assessment, every discharge summary, every telephone encounter note is a potential source of adverse event signals. A patient who develops a rash after starting a new antibiotic. A post-surgical patient whose wound becomes infected at a higher-than-expected rate. A medication interaction that shows up as unexplained fatigue in a dozen patients. These are all documented. They're just not aggregated, classified, or surfaced to the people who need to act on them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Building a system that automatically detects adverse event mentions in clinical text transforms passive documentation into active surveillance. Instead of waiting for someone to voluntarily report, you scan every note as it's written. Instead of retrospective chart reviews, you get near-real-time signals. The payoff is faster safety responses, better pharmacovigilance, and potentially catching problems before they become widespread.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's talk about why "just search for drug side effects in notes" doesn't actually work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Finding Safety Signals in Clinical Prose
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Adverse Event Detection Is Harder Than It Sounds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The naive approach sounds simple: build a dictionary of known adverse events, search clinical notes for mentions, correlate with active medications, report matches. Five minutes on a whiteboard and you'd think this is a solved problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It isn't. Here's why.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Adverse events are often described implicitly.** A clinician rarely writes "adverse drug event: rash from amoxicillin." They write "new maculopapular rash, onset three days after starting amoxicillin, suspect drug reaction." Or they just write "rash, discontinue amoxicillin" and let the temporal proximity imply causation. Or they write "itchy bumps on arms" in a telephone note with no explicit connection to any medication at all. The further you get from explicit documentation, the harder extraction becomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Distinguishing expected from unexpected.** Chemotherapy causes nausea. Opioids cause constipation. Antihypertensives cause dizziness. These are expected, dose-dependent effects that are not safety signals in the traditional sense. A system that flags every mention of nausea in an oncology patient's chart would drown safety teams in noise. The interesting signals are the unexpected events: the antibiotic that causes liver injury, the antidepressant that triggers suicidal ideation, the medical device that fails at a higher rate than its literature suggests. Separating expected from unexpected requires knowing what's expected for each drug or intervention, which means maintaining or accessing a comprehensive knowledge base of known effects.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal reasoning is essential.** An adverse event implies causation (or at least temporal association) between an intervention and an outcome. "Patient developed rash" is not an adverse event if the rash started two weeks before the medication. "Patient had a fall" is not a medication-related event if the patient has a longstanding gait disorder unrelated to their current drugs. Determining whether the timing supports a causal relationship requires extracting temporal information from text that often uses relative time expressions ("since starting the new medication," "over the past few days," "shortly after the procedure").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Negation and hypothetical context.** "No signs of hepatotoxicity" is not an adverse event. "If the patient develops a rash, discontinue the medication" is a contingency instruction, not a reported event. "The patient's mother had an allergic reaction to penicillin" is family history, not a patient event. Clinical text is full of negations, hypotheticals, and attributions to other people. A system that doesn't handle these contexts will generate a catastrophic false positive rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Severity matters.** A mild headache that resolves on its own is different from a life-threatening anaphylactic reaction. Safety surveillance systems need to prioritize, and priority depends on severity. Extracting severity from clinical text is itself a complex problem: "mild," "moderate," "severe," "life-threatening," "resolved without intervention," "required hospitalization" are all severity signals, but they appear in varied forms across different documentation styles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Under-documentation is the norm.** Clinicians don't always document adverse events explicitly, especially mild ones. A patient mentions dry mouth as a side effect; the physician notes it mentally, adjusts nothing, and doesn't document it. These undocumented events are invisible to any NLP system. Your system will always undercount. The question is: by how much, and for which severity levels?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The NLP Architecture for Adverse Event Detection
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pipeline is more complex than standard clinical NER because it requires reasoning about relationships between entities, not just extracting entities in isolation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 1: Entity extraction.** Identify three classes of entities in the text:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Interventions:** Medications, procedures, devices, vaccines (anything that could cause an adverse event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Clinical events/findings:** Symptoms, signs, diagnoses, lab abnormalities (anything that could be an adverse event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Temporal expressions:** Dates, durations, relative time references ("after starting," "two days later," "since the surgery")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is relatively standard biomedical NER. Tools like MetaMap, cTAKES, SciSpacy, and cloud-based medical NLP services handle this well for explicit mentions. The challenge is coverage: your entity extraction needs to be comprehensive, because a missed medication mention means a missed adverse event relationship.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 2: Assertion classification.** For each extracted clinical event, determine its assertion status:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Present/Active:** The event is actually happening to this patient right now
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Absent/Negated:** Explicitly stated as not present ("no rash," "denies dizziness")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Hypothetical/Conditional:** Mentioned as a possibility, not a reality ("if rash develops")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Historical:** Happened in the past, not currently active
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Family history:** Happened to a family member, not the patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Only "present/active" events are candidates for adverse event classification. Everything else is filtered out. Assertion classification is covered in depth in Recipe 8.8, and it's one of the most impactful preprocessing steps for reducing false positives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 3: Relation extraction.** This is the core of adverse event detection: determining whether a clinical event is causally or temporally related to an intervention. This goes beyond co-occurrence in the same note. You need:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Temporal plausibility:** Did the event occur after the intervention? Within a plausible time window?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Explicit attribution:** Did the clinician state or imply a causal relationship? ("likely due to," "suspect drug reaction," "discontinue due to")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Proximity signals:** Are the intervention and event mentioned in the same sentence or paragraph? In the same section of the note?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Relation extraction can be approached as a classification problem: given a pair (intervention, event), classify the relationship as "causal," "temporal association," "no relation," or "negated relation." Training data for this task is scarce, which drives many systems toward rule-based or hybrid approaches.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 4: Severity and outcome classification.** Assign a severity level to each detected adverse event:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Grade 1: Mild (asymptomatic or mild symptoms, no intervention required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Grade 2: Moderate (minimal intervention, limits activities)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Grade 3: Severe (hospitalization, significant disability)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Grade 4: Life-threatening (urgent intervention required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Grade 5: Death
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) provides a standardized grading framework, but clinical text rarely uses CTCAE terminology explicitly. Inferring severity from narrative text ("required admission to ICU," "resolved without treatment," "patient was intubated") requires pattern matching against outcome indicators.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 5: Aggregation and signal detection.** Individual adverse event mentions become safety signals when aggregated across patients. A single report of dizziness with a new medication is an anecdote. Fifteen reports in two months is a signal. Aggregation requires:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Normalizing events to standard terminology (MedDRA preferred terms for adverse events)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Counting unique patients, not just mentions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Calculating observed-vs-expected ratios (disproportionality analysis)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Applying statistical methods to separate signal from noise
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Approaches to Relation Extraction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The "is this event caused by this intervention?" question is the hardest piece. Current approaches:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Rule-based patterns.** Look for explicit causal language: "due to," "caused by," "secondary to," "as a result of," "attributed to," "likely related to," "discontinue [drug] because of [event]." These patterns have very high precision (when they match, they're almost always correct) but limited recall (many adverse events are documented without explicit causal language).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Co-occurrence with temporal filtering.** If a medication and a clinical event appear in the same note, and the medication start date precedes the event, flag it as a candidate. Simple, but generates high false positive rates (patients on many medications will have many co-occurrences with unrelated events).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Supervised classification.** Train a model on annotated pairs of (intervention, event) with labels indicating whether a causal relationship exists. Requires substantial annotated data, which is expensive to create for this task. Performance varies significantly by drug class and event type.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Knowledge-base filtering.** Use a database of known adverse drug reactions (from FDA labels, SIDER, or FAERS data) to filter candidates. If the detected event is a known adverse effect of the detected drug, boost its relevance score. This helps with known reactions but misses novel signals (which are often the most valuable for pharmacovigilance).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid approaches.** Combine rule-based detection for explicit mentions, co-occurrence for implicit associations, and knowledge-base filtering for plausibility scoring. This is what most production systems actually use: layers of evidence that each contribute to an overall confidence score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The State of the Art
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Adverse event detection in clinical text sits at the intersection of several mature NLP capabilities (NER, assertion, temporal reasoning) but remains challenging as an end-to-end task. Key benchmarks:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The n2c2 (formerly i2b2) shared tasks have included medication extraction and adverse event detection components. Top systems achieve F1 scores in the 80-90% range for medication extraction and 60-75% for adverse event relation extraction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The TAC ADR (Text Analysis Conference Adverse Drug Reaction) track evaluated systems on FDA drug labels and social media. Clinical text presents different challenges than either source.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Production systems at large health systems typically achieve 70-85% precision on adverse event detection, with recall being much harder to measure (because the ground truth of "all actual adverse events" is unknowable from documentation alone).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The honest take: extraction of individual entities (drugs, symptoms) is a largely solved problem. The hard part is the relational reasoning, temporal logic, and severity classification that turn entity lists into actionable adverse event signals.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At a conceptual level:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Clinical Notes] → [Preprocessing/Section Detection]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     → [Entity Extraction: Drugs, Events, Temporal]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     → [Assertion Filtering: Remove negated/historical/hypothetical]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     → [Relation Extraction: Link events to interventions]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     → [Severity Classification]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     → [Normalization to MedDRA/standard codes]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     → [Aggregation and Signal Detection]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     → [Alert/Report Generation]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pipeline is sequential in the sense that each stage depends on the previous one, but within a stage, processing of individual notes is parallelizable. You're typically running this as a batch job over all notes generated in a time window (daily or hourly), with the aggregation step looking across the full result set.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Data flow considerations:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Input:** Clinical notes in HL7 FHIR DocumentReference format, CDA documents, or raw text from EHR integration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Intermediate:** Structured annotations (entity spans, assertion labels, relation triples)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Output:** Adverse event records with severity, causality confidence, and coded terms suitable for reporting to safety databases or feeding into pharmacovigilance dashboards
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Medical for entity extraction.** Comprehend Medical is AWS's healthcare-specific NLP service. It extracts medications (with dosage, frequency, route), medical conditions, and temporal expressions from clinical text. For the entity extraction stage of adverse event detection, it handles the heavy lifting of identifying drugs and clinical findings with their attributes. It also provides negation and assertion detection (whether a condition is negated, hypothetical, or conditional), which maps directly to our assertion filtering stage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** Each note flows through a multi-stage pipeline: extract entities, classify assertions, detect relations, score severity. Lambda handles this orchestration with step-by-step processing. For batch workloads (processing a day's worth of notes), Lambda integrates with SQS for reliable, scalable note-by-note processing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SQS for reliable note queuing.** Clinical notes arrive continuously as they're signed in the EHR. SQS provides a durable queue that decouples note ingestion from processing, handles retries on transient failures, and lets you scale processing independently of arrival rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for adverse event storage.** Detected adverse events need fast lookup by patient, by medication, and by time window. DynamoDB's flexible key structure supports these access patterns, and its TTL feature can manage retention policies for different severity levels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for note storage and audit trail.** Raw notes and intermediate processing artifacts need durable, encrypted storage. S3 provides the audit trail: which notes were processed, what was extracted, and what decisions the system made.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Neptune for aggregation and signal detection.** When you move from individual adverse events to population-level signals, you need to query relationships: which patients had which events on which drugs during which time periods. Neptune's graph database structure supports the disproportionality analysis and pattern detection that pharmacovigilance requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring and alerting.** Pipeline health metrics, extraction confidence distributions, and high-severity event alerts all flow through CloudWatch. When the system detects a Grade 3+ event, you want a real-time alert, not a batch report.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[EHR Integration\nHL7/FHIR Feed] -->|New signed notes| B[SQS Queue\nnotes-to-process]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B --> C[Lambda\nnote-processor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Raw note text| D[S3\nnotes-archive/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Extract entities| E[Amazon Comprehend Medical]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Entities + assertions| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Relation extraction\n+ severity scoring| F[Lambda\nae-classifier]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Detected AEs| G[DynamoDB\nadverse-events]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|High severity| H[CloudWatch Alarm\n+ SNS Alert]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Batch aggregation| I[Lambda\nsignal-aggregator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I -->|Graph queries| J[Amazon Neptune\nae-signal-graph]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J -->|Signals above threshold| K[Safety Dashboard\n/ Reporting]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style E fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style G fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style J fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend Medical, AWS Lambda, Amazon SQS, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3, Amazon Neptune, Amazon CloudWatch, Amazon SNS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend-medical:DetectEntitiesV2`, `comprehend-medical:InferRxNorm`, `sqs:ReceiveMessage`, `sqs:DeleteMessage`, `s3:PutObject`, `s3:GetObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `neptune-db:*` (scoped to cluster), `sns:Publish` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (clinical notes are PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; SQS: SSE-KMS; Neptune: encryption at rest; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SQS, Comprehend Medical, and CloudWatch Logs. Neptune requires VPC deployment. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls; audit trail for PHI access |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic clinical notes with planted adverse event mentions. MIMIC-III discharge summaries (de-identified) for development. Never use real patient notes in non-production environments. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Medical: ~$0.01 per 100 characters (a typical note is 2000-5000 chars = $0.20-0.50 per note at full entity detection). Batch pricing significantly lower. Lambda, SQS, DynamoDB negligible at moderate volumes. Neptune: instance-based pricing starting ~$0.35/hr for smallest instance. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | Extracts medication entities, medical conditions, and assertion attributes from clinical text |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestrates multi-stage NLP pipeline; runs relation extraction and severity classification logic |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SQS** | Queues incoming notes for reliable, scalable processing |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores individual adverse event detections with patient, drug, and time indexes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Archives raw notes and processing artifacts for audit |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Neptune** | Stores and queries drug-event-patient graph for signal aggregation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitors pipeline health; triggers alerts for high-severity events |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SNS** | Delivers real-time notifications for critical adverse events |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys across all data stores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Receive and archive the clinical note.** When a clinician signs a note in the EHR, it arrives in the processing queue via an integration feed (HL7 ADT message, FHIR subscription, or direct EHR integration). The first thing we do is archive the raw note in durable storage. This serves two purposes: audit compliance (every piece of PHI we process must be traceable) and reprocessing capability (when models improve, we can run historical notes through the updated pipeline). Skip this step and you lose the ability to explain or reproduce any detection the system makes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION receive_note(queue_message):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Parse the incoming message to extract note metadata and text content.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The message format depends on your EHR integration: HL7, FHIR, or custom.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     note_id      = queue_message.note_identifier      // unique ID from the EHR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_id   = queue_message.patient_identifier   // who the note belongs to
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     note_text    = queue_message.document_text        // the full clinical note content
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     note_date    = queue_message.service_date         // when the clinical encounter occurred
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     note_type    = queue_message.document_type        // progress note, discharge summary, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Archive the raw note before any processing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This creates an immutable record: "we received this exact text at this exact time."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     archive_path = "notes-archive/{year}/{month}/{note_id}.json"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     STORE to S3 at archive_path:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         note_id, patient_id, note_text, note_date, note_type,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         received_timestamp = current UTC time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN note_id, patient_id, note_text, note_date, note_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Extract medical entities using Comprehend Medical.** This is where the NLP engine does the heavy lifting. We send the clinical note text to Amazon Comprehend Medical's `DetectEntitiesV2` API, which returns structured entities for medications, medical conditions, anatomy, test results, and temporal expressions. Each entity comes with a confidence score, character offset positions, and crucially, trait attributes that tell us whether the mention is negated, hypothetical, or a diagnosis. We also call `InferRxNorm` to normalize medication mentions to standard RxNorm codes (this enables cross-note aggregation later, because "amlodipine" and "Norvasc" need to resolve to the same thing). Skip this step and you're writing regex patterns against clinical text, which is a path to madness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_entities(note_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Call Comprehend Medical to detect all medical entities in the note.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // DetectEntitiesV2 returns entities categorized by type with confidence scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     entity_response = call ComprehendMedical.DetectEntitiesV2 with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Text = note_text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Separate entities by category for downstream processing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     medications = []    // drugs, dosages, routes, frequencies
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     conditions  = []    // symptoms, diagnoses, signs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     temporals   = []    // dates, durations, relative time expressions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each entity in entity_response.Entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF entity.Category == "MEDICATION":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Capture the medication with all its attributes (dose, route, frequency)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // and its traits (negation status).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to medications: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text:       entity.Text,                    // "amlodipine 10mg"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 type:       entity.Type,                    // GENERIC_NAME, BRAND_NAME, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 attributes: entity.Attributes,             // dose, route, frequency details
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 traits:     entity.Traits,                 // NEGATION, PAST_HISTORY, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: entity.Score,                  // 0.0 to 1.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 offset:     (entity.BeginOffset, entity.EndOffset)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF entity.Category == "MEDICAL_CONDITION":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to conditions: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text:       entity.Text,                    // "orthostatic dizziness"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 type:       entity.Type,                    // DIAGNOSIS, SIGN_SYMPTOM, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 traits:     entity.Traits,                 // NEGATION, HYPOTHETICAL, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: entity.Score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 offset:     (entity.BeginOffset, entity.EndOffset)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF entity.Category == "TIME_EXPRESSION":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to temporals: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text:       entity.Text,                    // "since starting medication"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 type:       entity.Type,                    // TIME_TO_MEDICATION_NAME, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: entity.Score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 offset:     (entity.BeginOffset, entity.EndOffset)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Normalize medication names to RxNorm codes for consistent aggregation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each med in medications:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         rxnorm_response = call ComprehendMedical.InferRxNorm with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             Text = med.text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF rxnorm_response has concepts with score > 0.7:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             med.rxnorm_code = top concept's RxNorm CUI
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             med.rxnorm_name = top concept's preferred description
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN medications, conditions, temporals
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Filter by assertion status.** Not every medical condition mention represents something actually happening to the patient. "Denies chest pain" mentions chest pain but explicitly negates it. "Family history of stroke" attributes the event to someone else. "If the patient develops a rash, stop the medication" is a hypothetical instruction. This step filters the extracted conditions to keep only those that are asserted as present and active in the patient. Comprehend Medical provides trait flags for negation and other contextual attributes, which we use as the primary filter. This single step typically removes 30-50% of extracted conditions from consideration, dramatically reducing false positives downstream.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION filter_active_conditions(conditions):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Keep only conditions that represent real, current patient findings.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Comprehend Medical attaches "Traits" to each entity indicating context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     active_conditions = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each condition in conditions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         is_negated      = any trait in condition.traits has Name == "NEGATION"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         is_hypothetical = any trait in condition.traits has Name == "HYPOTHETICAL"  // TODO: verify trait name in current API
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         is_family_hx    = any trait in condition.traits has Name == "FAMILY_HISTORY" // TODO: verify if CM exposes this directly
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF NOT is_negated AND NOT is_hypothetical AND NOT is_family_hx:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // This condition is asserted as present in the patient. Keep it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to active_conditions: condition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Otherwise discard: negated, hypothetical, or family history mentions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // are not adverse events happening to this patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN active_conditions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Detect adverse event relationships.** This is the core logic: for each active condition, determine whether it might be causally linked to a medication the patient is taking. We use a layered approach combining explicit causal language detection, temporal plausibility, and knowledge-base lookup. Each layer contributes evidence; the combined score determines whether we classify the pair as a detected adverse event. This is where most false positives and false negatives originate. The causal language patterns have high precision but miss implicit mentions. The temporal co-occurrence check has high recall but low precision. The knowledge base filters out implausible combinations but can't detect novel reactions. The layers compensate for each other's weaknesses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Known causal language patterns in clinical documentation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // High precision: if these phrases connect a drug to a symptom, it's almost always intentional.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CAUSAL_PATTERNS = [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "due to", "caused by", "secondary to", "related to",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "attributed to", "as a result of", "likely from",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "suspect reaction to", "discontinue .* because",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "hold .* due to", "adverse effect of", "side effect"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION detect_adverse_events(medications, active_conditions, temporals, note_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     detected_events = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each condition in active_conditions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each medication in medications:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             evidence_score = 0.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             evidence_reasons = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Layer 1: Explicit causal language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Search the text between (or near) the medication and condition mentions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // for phrases that explicitly link them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             text_between = extract text from note between medication.offset and condition.offset
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each pattern in CAUSAL_PATTERNS:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF pattern matches in text_between (case-insensitive):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     evidence_score += 0.6   // strong signal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     append to evidence_reasons: "explicit_causal_language: " + pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     BREAK  // one match is sufficient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Layer 2: Temporal plausibility.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Check if any temporal expression links the condition to the medication timing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each temporal in temporals:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF temporal suggests condition followed medication:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     // Phrases like "since starting," "after beginning," "two days after"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     evidence_score += 0.3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     append to evidence_reasons: "temporal_association: " + temporal.text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     BREAK
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Layer 3: Proximity in text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // If both entities appear in the same sentence or within a short span,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // there's a higher chance the clinician was connecting them mentally.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             character_distance = absolute(condition.offset.start - medication.offset.end)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF character_distance < 200:  // roughly same sentence or adjacent sentences
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 evidence_score += 0.1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 append to evidence_reasons: "text_proximity"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Layer 4: Knowledge-base plausibility check.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Is this a known adverse effect of this drug? Boosts confidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Uses a preloaded lookup table derived from FDA drug labels or SIDER database.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF medication.rxnorm_code EXISTS in KNOWN_ADR_DATABASE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 known_events = KNOWN_ADR_DATABASE[medication.rxnorm_code]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF condition.text (normalized) matches any entry in known_events:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     evidence_score += 0.2
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     append to evidence_reasons: "known_adr_match"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Threshold: only flag pairs with sufficient combined evidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF evidence_score >= 0.4:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 append to detected_events: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     medication:       medication.text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     rxnorm_code:      medication.rxnorm_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     event:            condition.text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     evidence_score:   evidence_score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     evidence_reasons: evidence_reasons,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     medication_offset: medication.offset,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     condition_offset:  condition.offset
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN detected_events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Classify severity.** Each detected adverse event needs a severity grade. Clinical text rarely uses standardized severity terminology, so we infer severity from contextual clues: whether the event led to hospitalization, required intervention, resolved on its own, or caused lasting harm. This classification drives prioritization in the safety dashboard and determines whether a real-time alert is warranted. A Grade 1 event (mild headache, self-resolved) goes into the database for aggregation. A Grade 3+ event (hospitalization, life-threatening) triggers an immediate notification to the safety team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Severity indicators extracted from surrounding clinical context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SEVERITY_INDICATORS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "grade_4_life_threatening": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "ICU", "intubated", "code blue", "life-threatening",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "anaphylaxis", "cardiac arrest", "emergency"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "grade_3_severe": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "admitted", "hospitalized", "transfusion required",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "surgical intervention", "disability", "prolonged"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "grade_2_moderate": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "medication change required", "dose reduction",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "additional treatment", "limits activities"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "grade_1_mild": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "mild", "self-limited", "resolved", "no intervention",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "tolerable", "asymptomatic"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION classify_severity(detected_event, note_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Look at the text surrounding the adverse event mention for severity clues.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check within a window of ~500 characters around the condition mention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     context_window = extract 500 characters around detected_event.condition_offset from note_text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check severity indicators from most severe to least (first match wins).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each grade in [grade_4, grade_3, grade_2, grade_1]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each indicator in SEVERITY_INDICATORS[grade]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF indicator found in context_window (case-insensitive):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 RETURN grade, indicator   // return both the grade and what matched
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Default: if no severity indicators found, assume Grade 2 (moderate).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Rationale: if the clinician documented it at all, it likely required some attention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Grade 1 events are often not documented. Absence of severity language
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // suggests a moderate event rather than a trivial one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN "grade_2_moderate", "default_no_indicators"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Store and alert.** Write the detected adverse event to the database with all metadata (patient, medication, event, severity, evidence, source note). For high-severity events (Grade 3+), fire a real-time alert to the safety team via SNS. For all events, the record becomes available for batch aggregation and signal detection. The storage schema supports multiple access patterns: lookup by patient (for clinical review), by medication (for drug-level surveillance), and by time window (for trend detection).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_and_alert(note_id, patient_id, note_date, detected_event, severity, severity_indicator):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Build the adverse event record with full traceability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ae_record = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ae_id:              generate unique ID,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:         patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         note_id:            note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         note_date:          note_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         medication:         detected_event.medication,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         rxnorm_code:        detected_event.rxnorm_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         event_description:  detected_event.event,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         severity:           severity,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         severity_indicator: severity_indicator,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         evidence_score:     detected_event.evidence_score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         evidence_reasons:   detected_event.evidence_reasons,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         detection_timestamp: current UTC time,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status:             "pending_review"   // all detections start as pending
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write to DynamoDB. Partition key: patient_id. Sort key: detection_timestamp.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // GSI on rxnorm_code + note_date for medication-level queries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     WRITE ae_record to DynamoDB table "adverse-events"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // High-severity alert: Grade 3 or above triggers immediate notification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF severity in ["grade_3_severe", "grade_4_life_threatening"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         PUBLISH to SNS topic "ae-critical-alerts":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             subject: "High-severity adverse event detected"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             message: ae_record (formatted for human readability)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Log metrics for monitoring pipeline health.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     EMIT CloudWatch metric: "AE_Detected" with dimensions [severity, medication_class]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN ae_record
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 7: Aggregate for signal detection (batch process).** Individual adverse event detections are useful for patient-level safety review, but the real pharmacovigilance value comes from aggregation. This step runs on a schedule (daily or weekly), queries all detected events in a time window, normalizes them, and applies disproportionality analysis to identify drug-event combinations that occur more frequently than expected. A single report of rash with a new antibiotic is noise. Fifteen reports in one month across twelve patients, when the expected rate is two, is a signal that warrants investigation. This batch process feeds the safety dashboard and can trigger escalation to regulatory reporting workflows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION aggregate_signals(time_window_days):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Query all detected adverse events from the specified time window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recent_events = QUERY DynamoDB "adverse-events" WHERE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         detection_timestamp > (now - time_window_days)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Group by normalized drug-event pair.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is where RxNorm normalization pays off: brand and generic names collapse together.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pair_counts = empty map   // key: (rxnorm_code, normalized_event) -> count of unique patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each event in recent_events:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pair_key = (event.rxnorm_code, normalize_event_term(event.event_description))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF pair_key not in pair_counts:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             pair_counts[pair_key] = { patients: empty set, total_mentions: 0 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pair_counts[pair_key].patients.add(event.patient_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pair_counts[pair_key].total_mentions += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply disproportionality analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compare observed count to expected count (from baseline rates).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     signals = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each pair_key, counts in pair_counts:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         unique_patients = size of counts.patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         expected_rate   = lookup_expected_rate(pair_key.rxnorm_code, pair_key.event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF unique_patients >= 3 AND (unique_patients / expected_rate) > 2.0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Signal: this drug-event pair is occurring at >2x the expected rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // with at least 3 distinct patients. Warrants investigation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to signals: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 rxnorm_code:     pair_key.rxnorm_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 event_term:      pair_key.event,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 unique_patients: unique_patients,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 total_mentions:  counts.total_mentions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 expected_rate:   expected_rate,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 ratio:           unique_patients / expected_rate,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 time_window:     time_window_days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write signals to Neptune graph for pattern exploration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each signal in signals:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         UPSERT to Neptune: drug node -> "SIGNAL" edge -> event node
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             with properties: signal metadata
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN signals
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter08.07-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a detected adverse event:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
